        <p class="key-stat-txt">people worldwide suffer from iron-deficiency anemia, making iron the <strong>#1 mineral deficiency on Earth</strong> — affecting more people than any other nutritional disorder, according to the World Health Organization.</p>
      </div>

      <p>In the United States alone, iron deficiency affects an estimated 10 million people, with women of childbearing age, pregnant women, vegans, vegetarians, and endurance athletes at highest risk. The National Institutes of Health reports that approximately 12% of women ages 12 to 49 have low iron stores. Left untreated, iron deficiency progresses to anemia — causing chronic fatigue, cognitive impairment, weakened immunity, and in pregnant women, increased risk of preterm delivery and low birth weight.</p>

      <p>Traditional iron tablets are effective but notorious for gastrointestinal side effects: constipation, nausea, stomach cramping, and dark stools. A 2021 study in <em>Alimentary Pharmacology & Therapeutics</em> found that up to 58% of patients prescribed oral iron supplements discontinued them within 2 months due to GI intolerance. Iron gummies solve this compliance crisis by delivering meaningful doses in a format that is easier on the stomach and far more pleasant to take daily. If you are also looking at overall <a href="/vitamins/">vitamin and mineral supplementation</a>, iron is one of the most critical gaps to address first.</p>

