    <!-- How We Tested -->
    <section>
      <h2>How We Tested These Iron Gummies</h2>

      <div class="tested-box">
        <h3>Our Testing Methodology</h3>
        <p>Our evaluation was designed to provide evidence-based guidance that goes beyond marketing claims. Here is exactly how we arrived at our rankings:</p>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Independent Procurement:</strong> All 30+ iron gummies were purchased at full retail price from Amazon, Target, Walmart, Whole Foods, and brand websites. We accepted no free samples, sponsorships, or promotional considerations.</li>
          <li><strong>Iron Form and Dose Verification:</strong> Each formula was analyzed against published clinical literature. We verified iron form (ferrous vs. ferric vs. chelated vs. whole food), elemental iron content, vitamin C inclusion, and whether the stated dose aligned with doses used in peer-reviewed studies.</li>
          <li><strong>Third-Party Testing Audit:</strong> We verified all testing claims by checking USP, NSF International, USDA Organic, and Non-GMO Project databases directly. Products claiming independent testing without verifiable certifications were flagged.</li>
          <li><strong>4-Week Tolerance Panel:</strong> A panel of 16 adults (ages 20-65, 12 women and 4 men) tested each product for 4 consecutive weeks. Participants tracked energy levels, GI symptoms (constipation, nausea, cramping), stool changes, and subjective well-being using standardized daily logs.</li>
          <li><strong>Absorption Enhancement Audit:</strong> We specifically evaluated whether each formula included vitamin C or other absorption enhancers, the dose of vitamin C relative to clinical efficacy thresholds, and whether any inhibitors (calcium, tannins) were present in the formula.</li>
          <li><strong>Taste and Compliance:</strong> Every product was rated on flavor, texture, aftertaste (particularly metallic notes), and overall enjoyment on a 1-10 scale. Iron supplements are notoriously difficult to make palatable, so taste is a critical compliance factor.</li>
          <li><strong>Value Calculation:</strong> Total cost was divided by servings and weighted against iron dose, iron form quality, additional nutrients, and testing certifications to calculate true per-serving value.</li>
        </ol>

        <p>Final rankings use a weighted scoring model: Iron Form and Dose (25%), Third-Party Testing (20%), Tolerance Panel Results (25%), Absorption Enhancement (10%), Taste (10%), and Value (10%).</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Who Needs Iron Gummies -->
    <section>
      <h2>Who Needs Iron Gummies? A Guide by Lifestyle</h2>

      <p>Iron supplementation is not one-size-fits-all. Your ideal dose, iron form, and product depend on your specific risk factors. Here is a breakdown by population:</p>

      <div class="info-cards">
        <div class="info-card">
          <div class="info-card-ico">&#9792;</div>
          <h3>Women with Heavy Periods</h3>
          <p><strong>Recommended dose:</strong> 18 mg/day. <strong>Best picks:</strong> BeLive, Zahler, or Nature Made (all 18 mg). Menstrual blood loss is the #1 cause of iron deficiency in premenopausal women. If your periods last 7+ days or you change pads/tampons every 1-2 hours, request a ferritin test from your doctor.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-card">
          <div class="info-card-ico">&#x1F930;</div>
          <h3>Pregnant & Trying to Conceive</h3>
          <p><strong>Recommended dose:</strong> 27 mg/day (pregnancy). <strong>Best picks:</strong> Consult your OB-GYN. Most iron gummies provide 10-18 mg, which supplements but does not replace prenatal iron. See our <a href="/best-prenatal-gummies/">best prenatal gummies</a> for formulas designed specifically for pregnancy.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-card">
          <div class="info-card-ico">&#x1F33F;</div>
          <h3>Vegans & Vegetarians</h3>
          <p><strong>Recommended dose:</strong> 1.8x standard RDA (32 mg/day for women). <strong>Best picks:</strong> Naturelo (vegan-certified) or Garden of Life (organic, plant-based). Pair with vitamin C-rich foods at every meal to maximize non-heme iron absorption.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-card">
          <div class="info-card-ico">&#x1F3C3;</div>
          <h3>Athletes & Active Adults</h3>
          <p><strong>Recommended dose:</strong> 18 mg/day for female athletes; 8-11 mg for males. <strong>Best picks:</strong> BeLive or Vitafusion (18 mg with vitamin C). Up to 56% of female distance runners have depleted iron stores. Monitor ferritin levels every 3-6 months during heavy training.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Warn box -->
      <div class="warn-box">
        <div class="warn-box-ico">!</div>
        <p><strong>Do NOT self-supplement iron without testing.</strong> Unlike water-soluble vitamins, excess iron accumulates in organs and can cause serious damage. People with hemochromatosis (iron overload) — which affects 1 in 200 Americans — must avoid iron supplements entirely. Always get a serum ferritin test before starting iron supplementation.</p>
